  { q: 'How much does indoor air quality improvement cost in Tampa?', a: 'IAQ investments scale with the problem. Basic upgrades run $150 to $450 (high-efficiency filter conversion, UV lamp). Mid-tier solutions run $700 to $1,800 (whole-home air purifier, dehumidifier, ERV). Complete packages including duct sealing, purifier, dehumidifier, and testing run $2,400 to $4,800. We start with free testing, actual numbers from your home, not a pressure pitch.' },
  { q: 'My house is dusty and my family has allergies. What actually works?', a: 'In Tampa Bay, three things move the needle most: upgrading the filter from a 1-inch MERV 8 to a 4-inch MERV 13 cartridge (captures 98% of allergens vs. 42%), sealing return-air leaks in the attic that pull dusty air into the system, and adding UV-C in the air handler to kill mold on the coil. Duct cleaning is a supporting tactic, not a standalone fix.' },
  { q: 'Do I actually need a whole-home dehumidifier in Florida?', a: 'In some Tampa homes yes, in others no. Put a hygrometer in the middle of the house on a stormy afternoon. If indoor humidity consistently runs above 58% RH while the AC cycles normally, a dedicated dehumidifier is worth it. Homes with sealed ducts, proper sizing, and variable-speed equipment usually stay under 55% RH on their own.' },
  { q: 'What is an ERV and do I need one?', a: 'An ERV (Energy Recovery Ventilator) brings in fresh outdoor air while exchanging heat and humidity with the outgoing stale air, controlled ventilation without the energy penalty of cracking a window. In tight post-2015 Tampa homes, ERVs are often needed. In older leaky homes the envelope ventilates itself. We assess envelope tightness before recommending one.' },
  { q: 'Are UV lights in HVAC systems worth it?', a: 'For the right use case, yes. UV-C installed near the cooling coil prevents biofilm and mold on the coil surface, a measurable improvement in humid Florida attics. UV-C in the return-air duct does not sterilize passing air; contact time is too short. We install the coil-mounted version and skip the return-duct version.' },
  { q: 'Does air duct cleaning really help indoor air quality?', a: 'Duct cleaning helps in three specific cases: after a rodent infestation, after construction dust, or when visible mold is present at the registers. For general dust or allergy reduction, cleaning without filter and seal upgrades is largely theater, because ducts repopulate within 60 days. We will tell you honestly whether cleaning fits your situation.' },
  { q: 'Can you test my indoor air quality before recommending anything?', a: 'Yes. We offer a free 60-minute IAQ assessment with particulate counts (PM2.5 and PM10), CO2 levels, relative humidity across rooms, VOC screening, and a visual inspection of the filter, coil, drain, and return-air seals. The written report shows the actual problems so any investment is aimed at the right fix.' },
];

